'''Stephanie Morton''' (born 28 November 1990) is an Australian cyclist.  She was selected to represent [[Australia at the 2012 Summer Paralympics|Australia]] at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in cycling as [[Felicity Johnson]]'s tandem pilot.

==Personal==
Morton was born on 28 November 1990 in Adelaide, South Australia.<ref name=cyclingaus/><ref name=apc/> In July 2012, she was involved in a three-automobile accident that left her uninjured but carless.<ref name=moana/> {{As of|2012}}, she lives in [[Moana Heights, South Australia]]<ref name=moana>{{cite web|last=Harris |first=Lia |url=http://www.adelaidenow.com.au/news/south-australia/sa-paralympian-in-three-car-prang/story-e6frea83-1226432876629 |title=SA Paralympian in three car prang |publisher=adelaidenow |date=2012-07-23 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> where she is a student working on a Bachelors of Arts and Bachelor of Education in Primary Teaching.<ref name=cyclingaus/><ref name=apc/>

==Cycling==
Morton is a cyclist,<ref name=cyclingaus>{{cite web|url=http://www.cycling.org.au/?ID=41643 |title=Stephanie Morton |publisher=Cycling Australia |date= |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> and is a member of [[South Coast Cycling Club]].  She has a cycling scholarship with the [[South Australian Institute of Sport]], and is coached by David Short and Tim Decker.<ref name=cyclingaus/>

Morton started cycling competitively when she was fifteen years old.<ref name=cyclingaus/> Competing solo at the 2011 National Keirin Final, she finished second with only [[Anna Meares]] beating her.<ref name=cyclingaus/> She made her Australian national team debut at the 2011 Para-cycling Track World Championships.<ref name=cyclingaus/> She partnered with [[Felicity Johnson]] in 2011.<ref name=stufgred/>  She has said forming a friendship and real partnership was key for the pair's success.<ref name=stufgred/> In 2012, she participated in the UCI Para-cycling Track World Championships in [[Los Angeles]], while serving as the pilot for [[Felicity Johnson]], she finished first in the B tandem 1km time trial event.<ref name=losangeles>{{cite web|url=http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/299474/20120216/para-cyclones-golden-finish-worlds-campaign-au.htm#.UCo3VaMy1LY |title=Para-Cyclones Golden Finish to Worlds Campaign |publisher=Au.ibtimes.com |date=2012-02-16 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> She was selected to represent [[Australia at the 2012 Summer Paralympics|Australia]] at the [[2012 Summer Paralympics]] in cycling,<ref name=apc>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org.au/team/stephanie-morton |title=Stephanie Morton |publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee |location=Australia |date=2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=stufgred>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/partners-in-the-fast-lane-20120804-23mge.html |title=Partners in the fast lane |publisher=The Age |date=2012-08-05 |accessdate=2012-08-14}}</ref> she where will be [[Felicity Johnson]]'s pilot.<ref name=stufgred/><ref name=moana/>  Going into the Paralympics, the pair trained daily at the Gepps Cross velodrome.  Her car accident on 5 July 2012 made it difficult for her to get to daily training.<ref name=moana/>  Following the Paralympics, Morton wanted to continue her solo cycling career.<ref name=stufgred/>

